The problem is not that really, What I indicate is that it is not allowing the use of **DBexpression** with the IN condition.

```php
//OK
Model::find()
    ->where(['LIKE',new Expression("name"),"Mike"])
    ->all();

//OK
Model::find()
    ->where(['=>',new Expression("name"),"Mike"])
    ->all();


//ERROR-> Illegal offset type
Model::find()
    ->where(['IN',new Expression("name"),["Mike","Jonh"]])
    ->all();


//But this OK
Model::find()
    ->where(['IN',"name",["Mike","Jonh"]])
    ->all();
```

It is similar to this [https://github.com/yiisoft/yii2/issues/18134](url) but for the **IN** condition
